ted Kingdom\",\"dp\":\"Port Royal, Caroline, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":5,\"interesting\":true,\"ev\":[{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"\\\"It is no doubt correct that the first Jeter settled near Port Royal, Colony of Virginia in the early days of the eighteenth century\\\"\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"IMMIGRATION\",\"ti\":\"\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"Beginning of 18th Century\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Two Marriages\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\\\"The Jeter's who settled in Kentucky state that John Jeter immigrated from England in the beginning of the eighteenth century and settled eight miles from Port Royal in Caroline County, Virginia; that he married twice and eleven children by each marriage.\\\" \\\"No record is found of either of the marriages of John Jeter, but the name of his wife Elizabeth-no doubt his second wife-is signed to a 'deed of gift' to his son, John Jr. in Amelia County, Virginia in 1756.  It is said that, John Jeter Sr. was the father of 22 children, eleven by each marriage.\\\"\"}],\"sketch\":\"\",\"mem\":3,\"src\":6},{\"pos\":49,\"gen\":10,\"id\":\"GTXS-6HG\",\"name\":\"Elizabeth Vaughan\",\"life\":\"1685–1730\",\"bp\":\"St Martin in the Fields, Westminster, Middlesex, England\",\"dp\":\"Caroline, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":1,\"interesting\":false,\"ev\":[{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Baptism\",\"d\":\"28 February 1686\",\"pl\":\"St Martin in the Fields, Westminster, Middlesex, England\",\"desc\":\"\"}],\"sketch\":\"\",\"mem\":0,\"src\":2},{\"pos\":98,\"gen\":11,\"id\":\"GGMP-JB3\",\"name\":\"Martin Vaughn\",\"life\":\"1663–1745\",\"bp\":\"Spotsville, Surry, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"dp\":\"\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":0,\"interesting\":false,\"ev\":[],\"sketch\":\"\",\"mem\":0,\"src\":0},{\"pos\":197,\"gen\":12,\"id\":\"96D6-N64\",\"name\":\"Marichje Cosijn\",\"life\":\"1636–Deceased\",\"bp\":\"Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"dp\":\"\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":0,\"interesting\":false,\"ev\":[],\"sketch\":\"\",\"mem\":0,\"src\":0},{\"pos\":25,\"gen\":9,\"id\":\"K8HQ-6RR\",\"name\":\"Margaret Vaughan\",\"life\":\"1721–1775\",\"bp\":\"Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"dp\":\"South Carolina, British Colonial America\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\",\"South Carolina\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":5,\"interesting\":true,\"ev\":[{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Will of Cornelius Vaughan\",\"d\":\"6 November 1735\",\"pl\":\"King and Queen, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Legatees: Son John Vaughan / Son James Vaughan / Son Ambrose Vaughan / Son Cornelius Vaughan / my four youngest children Bridget, Cornelius, Elizabeth, Margaret and my unborn child / Mary Chapman, Ann Martin, Sarah Hudgin, Katharine Silvan, Christian Scott / Wife Elizabeth\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Will of Elizabeth Vaughan\",\"d\":\"14 November 1775\",\"pl\":\"Spotsylvania, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Legatees: my four children which are now alive, and my son Martin Vaughan's four children, his part to be equally divided amongst them, Cornelius Vaughan, Bridget Broadas, Elizabeth Pemberton, Margaret Geter/Witnesses: Nathan Hawkins & Edward Leavell/Executor: William Pemberton. Executors Bond dated November 19, 1778.\"}],\"sketch\":\"\",\"mem\":6,\"src\":9},{\"pos\":50,\"gen\":10,\"id\":\"MQ8P-J73\",\"name\":\"Cornelius Vaughan\",\"life\":\"1670–1735\",\"bp\":\"Spotsylvania, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"dp\":\"King and Queen, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":6,\"interesting\":true,\"ev\":[{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Land Grant\",\"d\":\"1 September 1696\",\"pl\":\"King and Queen, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Cornelius Vaughan and Thomas Jones were granted 450 acres of land adjoining the plantation of George Martin in King and Queen Co., for transporting nine persons to the Colony of Virginia\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Deed\",\"d\":\"8 April 1710\",\"pl\":\"Essex, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Thomas Tinsley of Essex County to Cornelius Vaughan of King and Queen County. Lease and release; for 3000 pounds of tobacco. 150 acres, part of 1100 acres granted to John May by patent 20 Oct. 1704 and by May sold to Tinsley ... Beverley's Swamp ... on the east side ... Witnesses: Robert Cooke, John Miller, William Scott.\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Will of Cornelius Vaughan\",\"d\":\"6 November 1735\",\"pl\":\"Drysdale Parish, Caroline, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Legatees: Son John Vaughan / Son James Vaughan / Son Ambrose Vaughan / Son Cornelius Vaughan / my four youngest children Bridget, Cornelius, Elizabeth, Margaret and my unborn child / Mary Chapman, Ann Martin, Sarah Hudgin, Katharine Silvan, Christian Scott / Wife Elizabeth\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Deed\",\"d\":\"6 December 1736\",\"pl\":\"Spotsylvania, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"A deed was conveyed by John Foster of St. George Parish, Spotsylvania County, VA to to Cornelius Vaughan and Martin Vaughan (the two youngest sons of Cornelius Vaughan, late Decd.) of Drysdale Parish, King and Queen County, VA. A price of 25 pounds had previously been paid to John Foster by the deceased Cornelius Vaughan. The land was 465 acres in St George Parish. /  Witnesses: Anthony Foster, John Chapman, Ignatius x Tureman. Dec. 7, 1736\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"DEED\",\"d\":\"6 April 1761\",\"pl\":\"Spotsylvania, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"conveyed to Cornelius and the sd. Martin Vaughan, sons of Cornelius Vaughan, Decd.\"}],\"sketch\":\"\",\"mem\":6,\"src\":15},{\"pos\":100,\"gen\":11,\"id\":\"PZBC-9NM\",\"name\":\"John Vaughn\",\"life\":\"1620–1685\",\"bp\":\"England\",\"dp\":\"Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":0,\"interesting\":false,\"ev\":[],\"sketch\":\"\",\"mem\":0,\"src\":0},{\"pos\":101,\"gen\":11,\"id\":\"PZBC-FSV\",\"name\":\"Ellen\",\"life\":\"1630–Deceased\",\"bp\":\"England\",\"dp\":\"Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":0,\"interesting\":false,\"ev\":[],\"sketch\":\"\",\"mem\":0,\"src\":0},{\"pos\":51,\"gen\":10,\"id\":\"LTZW-CBV\",\"name\":\"Elizabeth E Foster\",\"life\":\"1694–1775\",\"bp\":\"Spotsylvania, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"dp\":\"Spotsylvania, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":6,\"interesting\":true,\"ev\":[{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Will of Elizabeth Vaughan\",\"d\":\"14 November 1775\",\"pl\":\"Spotsylvania, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Legatees: my four children which are now alive, and my son Martin Vaughan's four children, his part to be equally divided amongst them, Cornelius Vaughan, Bridget Broadas, Elizabeth Pemberton, Margaret Geter / Witnesses:Nathan Hawkins & Edward Leavell /  Executor: William Pemberton. Executors Bond dated Nov. 19, 1778.\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Will Bonded\",\"d\":\"19 November 1775\",\"pl\":\"Spotsylvania, Virginia, United States\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_FACT\",\"ti\":\"Elizabeth Vaughan married 1st a Leavell and then a Pemberton\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"Cornelius and Elizabeth had a daughter Elizabeth who married Edward Leavell. Her second husband was William Pemberton. In Elizabeth's will (Cornelius' wife) she named her four living children: Margaret, Cornelius, Elizabeth and Bridget, and her son Martin's 4 children as legatees. Martin died about 1764. ELizabeth, wife of Cornelius, is named as a child of Robert Foster in Coppage/Coppege Chronicle, 1542-1975 by John E. Manahan and A. Maxim Coppa