fferently (more poorly) than for the same persons listed in the register.   Not only did the clerk use imaginative spellings, but his handwriting must have been difficult to read, for the Colonial Dames 1905 transcription of the same record renders scores of names differently than Chamberlayne’s transcription.  At any rate, no “Eastor” is mentioned anywhere in other records, thus this is sure\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"arrived in Louisa County, Virginia (then New Kent County), from England\",\"d\":\"1704\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"Quit Rent Rolls\",\"d\":\"1704\",\"pl\":\"New Kent, Virginia, British Colonial America\",\"desc\":\"Francis is shown with 300 acres\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_EVENT\",\"ti\":\"The vestry book of St. Paul’s Parish has been partly preserved and published, and contains several entries for Hesters, all concerning the processioning of land.\",\"d\":\"14 March 1709\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"The earliest recorded St. Paul’s processioning, carried out sometime in late 1708 or early 1709, and recorded on 14 March 1708/9, shows that the lands of Edward Bullock, Richard Bullock, Francis Hester, William Talley, and Mark Anthony were processioned as one of 39 precincts within the parish. The processioners’ return stated that “Fra: Hester being an Ancient man was not Able to Travel to see our Land processioned, but he saw his own, and so he was very well satisfied.”\"},{\"t\":\"OTHER_FACT\",\"ti\":\"St. Peter's Parish Episcopal Church may have been where George and Martha Washington were married, as well as the burial place of Francis Hester.\",\"d\":\"\",\"pl\":\"\",\"desc\":\"\"}],\"sketch\":\"\",\"mem\":4,\"src\":6},{\"pos\":2565,\"gen\":12,\"id\":\"PSKS-PDP\",\"name\":\"Elizabeth A Garland\",\"life\":\"1659–1739\",\"bp\":\"New Kent, New Kent, Virginia, United States\",\"dp\":\"St Martins Parish, Hanover, Virginia, United States\",\"states\":[\"Virginia\"],\"primary\":\"Virginia\",\"score\":0,\"interesting\":false,\"ev